{{Infobox protected area | name = Charlestown State Park | iucn_category = III | map = USA Indiana | map_width = 200 | map_caption = Map of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Indiana]] showing the location of Charlestown State Park | location = [[Clark County, Indiana|Clark County]], [[Indiana]], [[United States|USA]] | nearest_city = [[Charlestown, Indiana]] | coordinates = {{coords|38|25|48|N|85|37|48|W|display=inline, title}} | area_acre = 5100 | established = October 12, 1996 | visitation_num = 131,761 | visitation_year = 2008-2009 | governing_body = [[Indiana Department of Natural Resources]] }} [[File:Charlestown State Park Entrance.jpg|thumb|290px|Entrance of Charlestown State Park]] '''Charlestown State Park''' is an [[List of Indiana state parks|Indiana state park]] on {{convert|5100|acre|km2|2}} in [[Clark County, Indiana|Clark County]], [[Indiana]], in the [[United States]]. The park is on the banks of the [[Ohio River]], {{convert|1|mi|km|0}} east of [[Charlestown, Indiana|Charlestown]]. It was once part of the [[Indiana Army Ammunition Plant]] (INAAP), and was donated in separate parcels to the Indiana state government. In 1993, the state of Indiana was given {{convert|859|acre|km2|2}}, and in 1994 was given an additional {{convert|1125|acre|km2|2}} . When the park opened in 1996, it encompassed {{convert|2400|acre|km2|1}}. With an additional {{convert|2600|acre|km2|1}} given by the INAAP in 2004, the park has {{convert|5100|acre|km2|1}}, making it the third largest state park in Indiana.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hq.usace.army.mil/cepa/pubs/nov05/story16.htm |title=Old ammo plant cleaned up for new use |author=John Fleshman |accessdate=2007-04-02 |publisher=[[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070823213700/http://www.hq.usace.army.mil/cepa/pubs/nov05/story16.htm |archivedate=2007-08-23 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> The park attracts 131,000 people a year.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120908191654/http://www.news-tribune.net/archivesearch/local_story_107103248.html?start:int=30 The News and Tribune - SMALL-TOWN GROWING SPURT: Charlestown deals with growing population<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
==Features== The main feature of the park is various scenic trails overlooking [[Fourteen Mile Creek]], noted for being one of the oldest unglaciated stream valleys in the state. On the peninsula the creek forms where it meets the Ohio River stands an isolated bedrock ridge called the [[Devil's Backbone (rock formation)|Devil's Backbone]]. According to legend, the Devil's Backbone forms part of the remains of an ancient stone fortress built by Welsh adventurers who traveled to the Ohio Valley in the 12th century, though the story is unsubstantiated. The park does not provide any access to this peninsula from its trails. At one time there was a footbridge across the creek used for accessing the [[Rose Island (amusement park)|Rose Island amusement park]], but only concrete pilings remain on each side of the creek.
[[Devonian]] fossils and [[karst]] [[sinkhole]]s can be found in the park, in addition to 72 species of birds, including [[bluebird]]s, black [[vulture]]s and [[bald eagle]]s.
The park is scheduled for $3 million in improvements, which were delayed in January 2006 when workers building a new boat ramp found a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] cooking area dating back to 2,000 B.C. The remains of firepits and stone slabs that would be used to crack nuts were found, as well as Laurel chert, from which stone tools were made. Only once the archaeological surveys were done could work on the improvements, including a five-lane boat ramp and a riverfront walking trail, continue. In September, 2006 construction of the new boat ramps restarted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-tribune.net/siteSearch/apstorysection/local_story_256164749.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130222024313/http://www.news-tribune.net/siteSearch/apstorysection/local_story_256164749.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2013-02-22 |title=Boat ramp construction begins near Charlestown |author=David Mann |accessdate=2007-04-02 |publisher=The Evening News and The Tribune }}</ref> The boat ramps opened in June 2007.
In September 2011, the historic Portersville Bridge was relocated and reconstructed to cross the creek and connect Rose Island for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insideindianabusiness.com/newsitem.asp?ID=49956 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-04-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130126193314/http://www.insideindianabusiness.com/newsitem.asp?ID=49956 |archivedate=2013-01-26 |df= }}</ref>
==Future plans== There are still railroad tracks and private houses on the property, and the Indiana state government is still deciding what to do with them. Future developments confirmed by the state for the park include a swimming pool, access to Rose Island via a pedestrian bridge, more trails, improvements to the campground and cabins.<ref>''State leaders sure Charlestown State Park will see improvements'' {{cite web |url=http://www.news-tribune.net/local/local_story_202011721.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120906060714/http://www.news-tribune.net/local/local_story_202011721.html |archivedate=2012-09-06 |df= }}</ref>
