The '''Joint Air Force-Weber State University Satellite (JAWSAT)''' is an [[American military]] mini-satellite launched aboard a [[Minotaur (rocket)|Minotaur rocket]] on January 27, 2000 from [[Vandenberg Air Force Base|Vandenberg Air Force Base (VAFB)]] in [[California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://science1.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/1999/ast04nov99_1/ |title=Ham operators will get to help NASA with space experiment. |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=4 November 1999 |publisher=NASA Science |accessdate=7 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407093728/http://science1.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/1999/ast04nov99_1/ |archivedate=April 7, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> After its own launch, JAWSAT deployed four microsatellites: [[FalconSAT-1]], [[OCSE (satellite)|OCSE]], [[OPAL (satellite)|OPAL]], and [[ASUSat]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/spacewarn/spx555.html |title=SPACEWARN Bulletin Number 555 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1 February 2000 |website=NASA Space Science Data Coordinated Archive |publisher=[[NASA]] |accessdate=7 April 2014}}</ref> JAWSAT also carried [[NASA]]'s Plasma Experiment Satellite Test (PEST).

